\begin{tcbProblem}[label={problem:0071:question:Eng}]
	Consider the fraction, \( n \divslash d \), where \( n \) and \( d \) are positive integers.
	If \( n \less d \) and \( \HCF \lparen n \mathcomma d \rparen \equal 1 \), it is called a reduced proper fraction.

	If we list the set of reduced proper fractions for \( d \leq 8 \) in ascending order of size, we get:
	\begin{equation*}
		\frac{ 1 }{ 8 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 1 }{ 7 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 1 }{ 6 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 1 }{ 5 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 1 }{ 4 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 2 }{ 7 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 1 }{ 3 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 3 }{ 8 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ \mbftwo }{ \mbffive } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 3 }{ 7 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 1 }{ 2 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 4 }{ 7 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 3 }{ 5 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 5 }{ 8 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 2 }{ 3 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 5 }{ 7 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 3 }{ 4 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 4 }{ 5 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 5 }{ 6 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 6 }{ 7 } \mathcomma\ %
		\frac{ 7 }{ 8 }
	\end{equation*}
	It can be seen that \( 2 \fracslash 5 \) is the fraction immediately to the left of \( 3 \fracslash 7 \).

	By listing the set of reduced proper fractions for \( d \leq 1000000 \) in ascending order of size, find the numerator of the fraction immediately to the left of \( 3 \fracslash 7 \).
	\par%
